{"title_page": "Purdue Pharma", "text_new": "{{short description|American pharmaceutical company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Purdue Pharma L.P.\n| native_name      = Purdue Pharmaceuticals L.P.\n| logo             = Purdue-logo.gif\n| type             = [[private company|Private]]\n| foundation       = [[Manhattan|New York, New York]], USA<br>{{start date and age|1892}}\n| founders         = John Purdue Gray<br>George Frederick Bingham\n| location_city    = [[Stamford, Connecticut]]\n| location_country = U.S.\n| key_people       = Dr. Craig Landau ([[President (corporate title)|President]] & [[CEO]])<br>[[Arthur Sackler]]<br>[[Mortimer Sackler]]<br>[[Raymond Sackler]]\n| industry         = [[pharmaceutical company|Pharmaceuticals]]\n| num_employees    = 5,000 (worldwide)\n| revenue          = {{increase}} $3 billion (2017)\n| homepage         = {{URL|purduepharma.com}} (Global website)\n| footnotes        = {{reflist|group=*}}\n}}\n\n'''Purdue Pharma''' L.P. is a privately held [[pharmaceutical company]] founded by John Purdue Gray. It is owned principally by descendants of [[Mortimer Sackler|Mortimer]] and [[Raymond Sackler]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a12775932/sackler-family-oxycontin/|title=The Secretive Family Making Billions From the Opioid Crisis|last=Glazek|first=Christopher|date=2017-10-16|website=Esquire|access-date=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920060840/https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a12775932/sackler-family-oxycontin/|archive-date=2019-09-20|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain|title=The Family That Built an Empire of Pain|last=Keefe|first=Patrick Radden|date=2017-10-23|work=The New Yorker|accessdate=2018-01-19|issn=0028-792X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122073308/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain|archive-date=2018-01-22|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2007, it paid out one of the largest fines ever levied against a pharmaceutical firm for mislabeling its product [[OxyContin]], and three executives were found guilty of criminal charges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/18591525|title=Purdue Pharma, Execs to Pay $634.5 Million Fine in OxyContin Case|last=AP|date=2007-05-10|website=www.cnbc.com|access-date=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821020738/https://www.cnbc.com/id/18591525|archive-date=2019-08-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Van Zee|first=Art|date=February 2009|title=The Promotion and Marketing of OxyContin: Commercial Triumph, Public Health Tragedy|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=99|issue=2|pages=221\u2013227|doi=10.2105/AJPH.2007.131714|issn=0090-0036|pmc=2622774|pmid=18799767}}</ref> Although the company shifted its focus to abuse-deterrent formulations, Purdue continued to market and sell opioids, and continued to be involved in lawsuits around the [[opioid epidemic in the United States]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/opioid-talks-impasse-purdue-bankruptcy-filing-expected-n1051136|title=Opioid talks break down; Purdue owners balk at paying $4.5 billion|website=NBC News|access-date=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921141532/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/opioid-talks-impasse-purdue-bankruptcy-filing-expected-n1051136|archive-date=2019-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/09/11/759967610/purdue-pharma-reaches-tentative-deal-to-settle-thousands-of-opioid-lawsuits|title=Purdue Pharma Reaches Tentative Deal To Settle Thousands Of Opioid Lawsuits|website=NPR.org|access-date=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921114135/https://www.npr.org/2019/09/11/759967610/purdue-pharma-reaches-tentative-deal-to-settle-thousands-of-opioid-lawsuits|archive-date=2019-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Purdue filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection on September 15, 2019 in New York.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-purdue-pharma-bankruptcy-idUSKBN1W1058|title=OxyContin maker Purdue Pharma files for bankruptcy protection|date=2019-09-17|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921050011/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-purdue-pharma-bankruptcy-idUSKBN1W1058|archive-date=2019-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/15/health/purdue-pharma-bankruptcy-opioids-settlement.html|title=Purdue Pharma, Maker of OxyContin, Files for Bankruptcy|last=Hoffman|first=Jan|date=2019-09-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-09-21|last2=Walsh|first2=Mary Williams|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921101445/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/15/health/purdue-pharma-bankruptcy-opioids-settlement.html|archive-date=2019-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe company that became Purdue Pharma was founded in 1892 by medical doctors John Purdue Gray and George Frederick Bingham in [[Manhattan]] as the Purdue Frederick Company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.purduepharma.com/about/|title=About Purdue Pharma L.P.|author=|date=|website=www.purduepharma.com|accessdate=22 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906101503/http://www.purduepharma.com/about/|archive-date=6 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2018/purdue-university-statement-re-purdue-pharma.html|title=Purdue University statement re: Purdue Pharma|last=Service|first=Purdue News|website=www.purdue.edu|access-date=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921145953/https://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2018/purdue-university-statement-re-purdue-pharma.html|archive-date=2019-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1952, the company was sold to two other medical doctors, brothers [[Raymond Sackler|Raymond]] and [[Mortimer Sackler]], who relocated the business to [[Yonkers, New York]]. At the time, Purdue sold staples like earwax remover and laxatives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain|title=The Family That Built an Empire of Pain|first=Patrick Radden|last=Keefe|date=October 23, 2017|via=www.newyorker.com|access-date=October 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122073308/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain|archive-date=January 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The Sacklers' older brother, [[Arthur Sackler]], held a one-third option in the company, which was sold to his brothers after his death.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hyperallergic.com/422738/elizabeth-sackler-nan-goldin-opioid-epidemic/|title=Elizabeth A. Sackler Supports Nan Goldin in Her Campaign Against OxyContin|date=2018-01-22|work=Hyperallergic|access-date=2018-01-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123035116/https://hyperallergic.com/422738/elizabeth-sackler-nan-goldin-opioid-epidemic/|archive-date=2018-01-23|url-status=live}}</ref> Under the Sacklers, the company opened additional offices in [[New Jersey]] and [[Connecticut]]. The headquarters are in [[Stamford, Connecticut]].\n\nThe present-day company, Purdue Pharma L.P., was incorporated in 1991, and focuses on [[pain management]] medication, calling itself a \"pioneer in developing medications for reducing pain, a principal cause of human suffering\". In September 2015, the company's website said it had some 1,700 people on its payroll.<ref name=\"Purduepharma.com_About\">{{cite web | url=http://www.purduepharma.com/about/ | title=About Purdue Pharma L.P. | accessdate=September 8, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906101503/http://www.purduepharma.com/about/ | archive-date=September 6, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, the company announced it would acquire VM Pharma, thereby gaining access to worldwide development and commercial rights to an [[allosteric]] selective [[tropomyosin]] receptor [[kinase]] inhibitor program, i.e., the Phase II candidate VM-902A. The deal could generate more than $213 million for VM Pharma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genengnews.com/gen-news-highlights/purdue-pharma-acquires-trka-inhibitor-program-for-up-to-213m/81251701/|title=Purdue Pharma Acquires TrkA Inhibitor Program for Up to $213M+ - GEN|author=|date=|website=GEN|accessdate=22 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023063714/https://www.genengnews.com/gen-news-highlights/purdue-pharma-acquires-trka-inhibitor-program-for-up-to-213m/81251701/|archive-date=23 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe company has never had an affiliation with [[Purdue University]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/purdue-university-statement-says-indiana-school-has-no-ties-to-purdue-pharma/|title=Purdue University must remind people it has no ties to Purdue Pharma|website=www.cbsnews.com|access-date=2019-09-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914202159/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/purdue-university-statement-says-indiana-school-has-no-ties-to-purdue-pharma/|archive-date=2019-09-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nThe company's branches include Purdue Pharma L.P., The Purdue Frederick Company, Purdue Pharmaceutical Products L.P., and Purdue Products L.P.\nThe company's manufacturing takes place at three sites: Purdue Pharmaceuticals L.P., a plant located in [[Wilson, North Carolina]], the P.F. Laboratories, Inc. in [[Totowa, New Jersey]], and Rhodes Technologies L.P., in [[Coventry, Rhode Island]]. Purdue Pharma L.P. also has research labs in [[Cranbury, New Jersey]]. OxyContin is currently distributed throughout the U.S., Canada, and Mexico. Distribution takes place from the P.F. Laboratories in [[Totowa, New Jersey]].\n\n[[Rhodes Pharmaceuticals]] is a sister company that was established in [[Rhode Island]] in 2007. The company is one of the largest producers of off-patent generic opioids in the US.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crow |first1=David |title=Billionaire Sackler family owns second opioid drugmaker |url=https://www.ft.com/content/2d21cf1a-b2bc-11e8-99ca-68cf89602132 |website=Financial Times |accessdate=September 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180915225952/https://www.ft.com/content/2d21cf1a-b2bc-11e8-99ca-68cf89602132 |archive-date=September 15, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSister companies to Purdue that are also controlled by descendants of Mortimer and Raymond Sackler are [[Napp Pharmaceuticals]] in the United Kingdom and Mundipharma<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thefix.com/secretive-billionaire-family-behind-rise-oxycontin |author=Victoria Kim |title=The Secretive Billionaire Family Behind The Rise Of Oxycontin |publisher=The Fix |date=November 3, 2017 |accessdate=February 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223021904/https://www.thefix.com/secretive-billionaire-family-behind-rise-oxycontin |archive-date=February 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> that are selling opioids globally.\n\nNew drugs are being developed under other company names, such as Adlon Therapeutics and Imbrium. Both are based in the same building as their parent company in downtown Stamford, and share employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mysanantonio.com/business/article/FDA-approves-Purdue-Pharma-subsidiary-s-ADHD-13655418.php|title=FDA approves Purdue Pharma subsidiary's ADHD drug|author=Paul Schott|date=March 2019|access-date=2019-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306042804/https://www.mysanantonio.com/business/article/FDA-approves-Purdue-Pharma-subsidiary-s-ADHD-13655418.php|archive-date=2019-03-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Management==\nCraig Landau was appointed CEO on June 22, 2017.<ref name=\"New CEO\">{{cite web |title=Purdue Pharma appoints new CEO |url=https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/business/article/Purdue-Pharma-appoints-new-CEO-11239163.php |date=June 22, 2017 |publisher=[[Stamford Advocate]] |accessdate=May 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521204413/https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/business/article/Purdue-Pharma-appoints-new-CEO-11239163.php |archive-date=May 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He joined Purdue Pharma L.P. in 1999 and was chief medical officer and as vice president of R&D innovation, clinical and medical affairs. In 2013, he was appointed president and CEO of Purdue Pharma (Canada).<ref name=\"Landau\">{{cite web|title=Craig Landau |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=34123931&privcapId=264625 |date= |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy 2018, eight members of the [[Sackler family]] were listed to be active or former members of the Board of Directors.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/46ff5632-b1bd-11e8-99ca-68cf89602132 |author=David Crowe |title=What next for the Sacklers? A pharma dynasty under siege |newspaper=[[Financial Times]] |date=September 8, 2018 |accessdate=February 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327161404/https://www.ft.com/content/46ff5632-b1bd-11e8-99ca-68cf89602132 |archive-date=March 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> By early 2019, the Sacklers had left the Purdue Pharma board, leaving none on the panel. Steve Miller became chairman in July 2018, with a current board left of five members.<ref name=\"Sacklers Quite\">{{cite web |title=Sacklers quit Purdue Pharma board amid shifts for OxyContin maker |url=https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/business/article/Sacklers-quit-Purdue-Pharma-board-signaling-13742946.php |date=April 7, 2019 |work=[[Stamford Advocate]] |publisher=[[Stamford Advocate]] |accessdate=May 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190528151957/https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/business/article/Sacklers-quit-Purdue-Pharma-board-signaling-13742946.php |archive-date=May 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nPurdue Pharma makes pain medicines such as [[hydromorphone]], [[oxycodone]], [[fentanyl]], [[codeine]], and [[hydrocodone]]. It is widely known for the production of drugs such as MS Contin, Oxycontin, and Ryzolt. In 1972, Contin (a controlled drug-release system) was developed. In 1984, its extended-release formulation of morphine, MS Contin was released. In 1996 its extended-release formulation of oxycodone, OxyContin was released.<ref name=\"Purduepharma.com_About\" />\n\nThe controversy behind the company emerged as a result of the drugs that they made and how they carried high potential for addiction. The most commonly abused medications that the company produces are MS Contin and OxyContin. Both can be abused by crushing, chewing, snorting, or injecting the dissolved product. These ingestion methods create a significant risk to the abuser; they can result in overdose and death. Drug-seeking tactics that addicts undergo to obtain the medication include \"[[doctor shopping]]\", which is visiting a number of different physicians to obtain additional prescriptions and refusal to follow up with appropriate examinations. Along with the high potential for abuse among people without prescriptions, there is also a risk for physical dependency and reduced reaction or drug desensitization for patients that are prescribed them. Nevertheless, strong analgesic drugs remain indispensable to patients suffering from severe acute and cancer pain.<ref>World Health Organization. Cancer pain relief and palliative care. Geneva: WHO 1990</ref>\n\nOxyContin, introduced in 1995, was Purdue Pharma's breakthrough palliative for chronic pain. Under a marketing strategy that [[Arthur Sackler]] had pioneered decades earlier, the company aggressively pressed doctors to prescribe the drug, wooing them with free trips to pain-management seminars and paid speaking engagements. Sales soared.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/19/business/raymond-sackler-dead-of-purdue-pharma.html|title=Opinion - Raymond Sackler, Psychopharmacology Pioneer and Philanthropist, Dies at 97|first=Sam|last=Roberts|date=19 July 2017|accessdate=11 February 2018|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228212508/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/19/business/raymond-sackler-dead-of-purdue-pharma.html|archive-date=28 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The drug was marketed as \"smooth and sustained pain control all day and all night\" when taken on a 12-hour schedule and as having lower abuse potential than immediate-release oxycodone because of its time-release properties, even though there was no scientific evidence backing that conclusion and the addictive nature of opiates had been known for thousands of years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-10-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122073308/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain |archive-date=2018-01-22 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://opiateaddictionsupport.com/chasing-heroin-review-frontline-documentary/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307142536/http://opiateaddictionsupport.com/chasing-heroin-review-frontline-documentary/ |archive-date=2016-03-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> In these early years, Purdue Pharma was aware of OxyContin abuse, including \"reports that the pills were being crushed and snorted; stolen from pharmacies; and that some doctors were being charged with selling prescriptions,\" according to ''[[The New York Times]]'', based on a confidential Justice Department report that was revealed in May 2018. Over a hundred internal company memos between 1997 and 1999 included the words \"street value,\" \"crush,\" or \"snort.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Meier|first1=Barry|title=Origins of an Epidemic: Purdue Pharma Knew Its Opioids Were Widely Abused|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/29/health/purdue-opioids-oxycontin.html|accessdate=30 May 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|date=29 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530000118/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/29/health/purdue-opioids-oxycontin.html|archive-date=30 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the start of 2000, widespread reports of OxyContin abuse surfaced. The results obtained from a proactive abuse surveillance program called Researched Abused, Diversion, and Addiction-Related Surveillance (RADARS) sponsored by Purdue Pharma L.P. pronounced Oxycontin and hydrocodone the most commonly abused pain medications.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Cicero TJ, Inciardi JA, Mu\u00f1oz A |title=Trends in abuse of Oxycontin and other opioid analgesics in the United States: 2002-2004 |journal=Journal of Pain |volume=6 |issue=10 |pages=662\u201372 |year=2005 |pmid=16202959 |doi=10.1016/j.jpain.2005.05.004 |url=}}</ref> In 2012, New England Journal of Medicine published a study that found that \"76 percent of those seeking help for heroin addiction began by abusing pharmaceutical narcotics, primarily OxyContin\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Jason|title=Kingpins: OxyContin, Heroin, and the Sackler-Sinaloa Connection|url=https://addictionunscripted.com/kingpinsoxycontin-heroin-and-the-sackler-sinaloa-connection/|accessdate=4 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307210054/https://addictionunscripted.com/kingpinsoxycontin-heroin-and-the-sackler-sinaloa-connection/|archive-date=7 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and drew a direct line between Purdue's marketing of OxyContin and the subsequent heroin epidemic in the U.S.\n\nIn 2003, the Drug Enforcement Administration found that Purdue's \"aggressive methods\" had \"very much exacerbated OxyContin's widespread abuse.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain|title=The Family That Built an Empire of Pain|first=Patrick Radden|last=Keefe|date=23 October 2017|accessdate=27 March 2019|via=www.newyorker.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122073308/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain|archive-date=22 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA 2016, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' investigation reported that in many people OxyContin's 12-hour schedule does not adequately control pain, resulting in withdrawal symptoms including intense craving for the drug. The journalists suggested that this problem gives \"new insight into why so many people have become addicted.\" Using Purdue documents and other records, they claim that Purdue was aware of this problem even before the drug went to market but \"held fast to the claim of 12-hour relief, in part to protect its revenue [because] OxyContin's market dominance and its high price \u2014 up to hundreds of dollars per bottle \u2014 hinge on its 12-hour duration.\"<ref name=\"latimes_Hell_oxycontin_2016\">{{cite web |title='You want a description of hell?' OxyContin's 12-hour problem |url=http://www.latimes.com/projects/oxycontin-part1/ |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=October 18, 2017 |last1=Harriet |first1=Ryan |first2=Lisa |last2=Girion |first3=Scott |last3=Glover |date=May 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124015217/http://www.latimes.com/projects/oxycontin-part1/ |archive-date=January 24, 2018 |url-status=live }} This is an in-depth series.</ref>\n\nOxyContin became a blockbuster drug. \"Between 1995 and 2001, OxyContin brought in $2.8 billion in revenue for Purdue Pharma.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/10/business/11drug-web.html |title=In Guilty Plea, OxyContin Maker to Pay $600 Million |first=Barry |last=Meier |date=May 10, 2007 |access-date=October 26, 2017 |newspaper=The New York Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027035616/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/10/business/11drug-web.html |archive-date=October 27, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cumulative revenues had increased to US$31 billion by 2016<ref name=\"latimes_Hell_oxycontin_2016\"/> and US$35 billion by 2017.<ref name=\"newyorker_2017_Sackler\"/> According to a 2017 article in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Purdue Pharma is \"owned by one of America's richest families, with a collective net worth of thirteen billion dollars\".<ref name=\"newyorker_2017_Sackler\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain |series=A Reporter at Large |date=October 2017 |title=The Family That Built an Empire of Pain: The Sackler dynasty's ruthless marketing of painkillers has generated billions of dollars\u2014and millions of addicts |first=Patrick Radden |last=Keefe |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=October 26, 2017 |quote=\"According to Forbes, the Sacklers are now one of America's richest families, with a collective net worth of thirteen billion dollars\u2014more than the Rockefellers or the Mellons... While the Sacklers are interviewed regularly on the subject of their generosity, they almost never speak publicly about the family business, Purdue Pharma\u2014a privately held company, based in Stamford, Connecticut, that developed the prescription painkiller OxyContin.\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122073308/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain |archive-date=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live }} Indepth-analysis</ref> Many US states allege the family is worth more than $13 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49702413|title=Sackler family 'funnelled cash into Swiss banks'|date=September 14, 2019|via=www.bbc.com|access-date=September 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916180158/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49702413|archive-date=September 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In response to this and other journalism, photographer [[Nan Goldin]] launched the organization [[P.A.I.N.]], to pressure museums and other cultural institutions to divest from Sackler Family philanthropy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-06/sackler-family-faces-art-world-protests-with-purdue-under-siege|title=Artists Protest Sackler Family Through Museums That Bear Their Name|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bloomberg.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416181229/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-06/sackler-family-faces-art-world-protests-with-purdue-under-siege|archive-date=2019-04-16|url-status=live|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Purdue Pharma patented a new form of buprenorphine, which controls cravings and is used to treat addiction to opioids such as OxyContin.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ivanova |first1=Irina |title=OxyContin maker gets patent for drug to treat opioid addiction |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/oxycontin-maker-receives-patent-for-drug-to-treat-opioid-addiction |accessdate=9 September 2018 |agency=CBS News |date=7 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908123341/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/oxycontin-maker-receives-patent-for-drug-to-treat-opioid-addiction/ |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Oxycontin-related lawsuits==\nPurdue has been involved in measures against prescription drug abuse, particularly of [[OxyContin|Oxycontin]], an addiction-causing prescription drug which is among the drugs most commonly cited in connection with overdose deaths. In 2001, [[Connecticut Attorney General]] [[Richard Blumenthal]] issued a statement urging Purdue to take action regarding abuse of Oxycontin; he did note that while Purdue seemed sincere, there was little action being taken beyond \"cosmetic and symbolic steps.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/AG/cwp/view.asp?A=1776&Q=283348|title=CT Attorney General|first=Office of the Attorney|last=General|date=|website=www.ct.gov|accessdate=22 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061219073015/http://www.ct.gov/ag/cwp/view.asp?A=1776&Q=283348|archive-date=19 December 2006|url-status=live}}</ref> After Purdue announced plans to [[Pharmaceutical formulation|reformulate the drug]], Blumenthal noted that this would take time and that \"Purdue Pharma has a moral, if not legal obligation to take effective steps and address addiction and abuse even as it works to reformulate the drug.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/AG/cwp/view.asp?A=1776&Q=283344|title=CT Attorney General|first=Office of the Attorney|last=General|date=|website=www.ct.gov|accessdate=22 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061219073036/http://www.ct.gov/ag/cwp/view.asp?A=1776&Q=283344|archive-date=19 December 2006|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the [[West Virginia Attorney General]] sued Purdue for reimbursement of \"excessive prescription costs\" paid by the state. Saying that patients were taking more of the drug than they had been prescribed because the effects of the drug wore off hours before the 12-hour schedule, the state charged Purdue with [[deceptive marketing]]. In his ruling the trial judge wrote: \"Plaintiff's evidence shows Purdue could have tested the safety and efficacy of OxyContin at eight hours, and could have amended their label, but did not.\" The case never went to trial; Purdue agreed to settle by paying the state {{US$|10 million}} (equivalent to approximately ${{inflation|US|10|2004}}M in {{inflation/year|US}}) for programs to discourage drug abuse, with all the evidence remaining under seal and confidential.<ref name=\"latimes_Hell_oxycontin_2016\"/>\n\nIn May 2007, the company [[pleaded guilty]] to misleading the public about Oxycontin's risk of addiction and agreed to pay {{US$|600 million|long=no}} (equivalent to approximately ${{inflation|US|600|2007}}M in {{inflation/year|US}}) in one of the [[List of Largest Pharmaceutical Settlements|largest pharmaceutical settlements in U.S. history]]. The company's [[President (corporate title)|president]] (Michael Friedman), top lawyer (Howard R. Udell) and former [[Chief Medical Officer|chief medical officer]] (Paul D. Goldenheim) pleaded guilty as individuals to [[Pharmaceutical fraud#Off-label marketing|misbranding]] charges, a criminal violation and agreed to pay a total of {{US$|34.5 million}} in fines.<ref>Sue Lindsey, (May 11, 2007) [https://www.usatoday.com/money/economy/2007-05-10-1771944037_x.htm OxyContin Maker, Execs Guilty of Deceit] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120911005434/http://www.usatoday.com/money/economy/2007-05-10-1771944037_x.htm |date=2012-09-11 }} [[USA Today]] reproducing and [[Associated Press]] report</ref><ref>Barry Meier, (May 11, 2007) \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/11/business/11drug-web.html?_r=1&hp In Guilty Plea, OxyContin Maker to Pay $600 Million\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611003513/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/11/business/11drug-web.html?_r=1&hp |date=2015-06-11 }}, New York Times</ref> Friedman, Udell and Goldenheim agreed to pay {{US$|19 million}}, {{US$|8 million}} and {{US$|7.5 million}}, respectively. In addition three top executives were charged with a felony and sentenced to 400 hours of [[Community service#Court ordered service|community service]] in drug treatment programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.domain-b.com/industry/pharma/2007/20070722_purdue_pharma.html|title=domain-b.com : Purdue Pharma fined $634 million for OxyContin deaths; executives punished|author=|date=July 22, 2007|website=www.domain-b.com|accessdate=22 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206000554/http://domain-b.com/industry/pharma/2007/20070722_purdue_pharma.html|archive-date=6 February 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn October 4, 2007, Kentucky officials sued Purdue because of widespread Oxycontin abuse in Appalachia. A lawsuit filed by Kentucky then-Attorney General [[Greg Stumbo]] and Pike County officials demanded millions in compensation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/economy/2007-10-04-3869518294_x.htm|title=Kentucky sues makers of OxyContin - USATODAY.com|author=|date=|website=usatoday30.usatoday.com|accessdate=22 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814191254/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/economy/2007-10-04-3869518294_x.htm|archive-date=14 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Eight years later, on December 23, 2015, Kentucky settled with Purdue for $24 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/kentucky-settles-lawsuit-with-oxycontin-maker-for-24-million/|title=Kentucky settles lawsuit with OxyContin maker for $24 million|website=www.cbsnews.com|access-date=2016-05-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430040604/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/kentucky-settles-lawsuit-with-oxycontin-maker-for-24-million/|archive-date=2016-04-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, the city of [[Everett, Washington]] sued Purdue based on increased costs for the city from the use of oxycontin as well as Purdue not intervening when they noted odd patterns of sale of their product, per agreement in the 2007 suit noted above. The allegations include not following legal agreements to track suspicious excess ordering or potential black market usage. False clinics created by unscrupulous doctors using homeless individuals as 'patients' to purchase oxycontin, then sell to the citizens of Everett was the factual basis of the suit.<ref name=\"Harriet Ryan\">{{citation|title=City devastated by OxyContin use sues Purdue Pharma, claims drugmaker put profits over citizens' welfare|author=Harriet Ryan|date=January 19, 2017|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-oxycontin-lawsuit-20170118-story.html|access-date=May 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601133439/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-oxycontin-lawsuit-20170118-story.html|archive-date=June 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Scott North\">{{citation|newspaper=Everett Herald|title=Everett's suit against OxyContin maker moves to federal court|author=Scott North|date=February 20, 2017|url=http://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-suit-against-oxycontin-maker-moves-to-federal-court/|access-date=May 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228194350/http://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-suit-against-oxycontin-maker-moves-to-federal-court/|archive-date=February 28, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Morning Edition\">{{citation|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/02/03/513196772/u-s-city-sues-oxycontin-maker-for-contributing-to-opiod-crisis|title=U.S. City Sues OxyContin Maker For Contributing To Opioid Crisis|work=[[Morning Edition]]|publisher=NPR|date=February 3, 2017|access-date=April 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313190130/https://www.npr.org/2017/02/03/513196772/u-s-city-sues-oxycontin-maker-for-contributing-to-opiod-crisis|archive-date=March 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe blackmarket sale of the drug out of legal pharmacies based in Los Angeles with distributions points in Everett is also part of the experience of the city. No intervention was made by Purdue to contact the DEA for years despite knowing of the practice and the overuse and sale of their product. The suit is asking for a yet to be determined reimbursement related to costs of policing, housing, health care, rehabilitation, criminal justice system, park and recreations department, as well as to the loss of life or compromised quality of life of the citizens of Everett directly.<ref name=\"Harriet Ryan\"/><ref name=\"Scott North\"/><ref name=\"Morning Edition\"/>\n\nIn May 2018, six states \u2014 Florida, Nevada, North Carolina, North Dakota, Tennessee and Texas \u2014 filed lawsuits charging deceptive marketing practices, adding to 16 previously filed lawsuits by other U.S. states and Puerto Rico.<ref name=\"Reuters May 10, 2018\">{{cite web |last1=Bellon |first1=Tina |title=U.S. state lawsuits against Purdue Pharma over opioid epidemic mount |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-opioids-litigation/u-s-state-attorneys-general-sue-purdue-pharma-over-opioid-epidemic-idUSKCN1IG2WU |website=Reuters |accessdate=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614152013/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-opioids-litigation/u-s-state-attorneys-general-sue-purdue-pharma-over-opioid-epidemic-idUSKCN1IG2WU |archive-date=14 June 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"USA Today May 2018\">{{cite web |last1=Moritz |first1=John C. |title=6 states sue maker of OxyContin as they battle expenses, human costs of opioid crisis |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2018/05/15/six-attorney-generals-opioid-lawsuits/612721002/ |website=USA TODAY |publisher=Corpus Christi (Texas) Caller Times |accessdate=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528110904/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2018/05/15/six-attorney-generals-opioid-lawsuits/612721002/ |archive-date=28 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> By January 2019, 36 states were suing Purdue Pharma. Massachusetts attorney general Maura Healey complains in her lawsuit that eight members of the Sackler family are \"personally responsible\" for the deception. She alleges they \"micromanaged\" a \"deceptive sales campaign.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/purdue-pharma-lawsuit-massachusetts-attorney-general-blames-sackler-family-for-creating-opioid-crisis-oxycontin/|title=Family behind OxyContin maker engineered opioid crisis, Massachusetts AG says|last=|first=|date=24 January 2019|website=CBS News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190127234253/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/purdue-pharma-lawsuit-massachusetts-attorney-general-blames-sackler-family-for-creating-opioid-crisis-oxycontin/|archive-date=27 January 2019|url-status=live|access-date=2019-01-28}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Purdue Pharma reached a $270m settlement in a lawsuit,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/5732644-Oklahoma-sopioidlawsuitpetition.html|title=Oklahoma'sopioidlawsuitpetition|last=Frontier)|first=Kassie McClung (The|website=www.documentcloud.org|access-date=2019-03-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327071316/https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/5732644-Oklahoma-sopioidlawsuitpetition.html|archive-date=2019-03-27|url-status=live}}</ref> filed by Oklahoma, which claimed its opioids contributed to the deaths of thousands of people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/26/health/opioids-purdue-pharma-oklahoma.html|title=Purdue Pharma and Sacklers Reach $270 Million Settlement in Opioid Lawsuit|last=Hoffman|first=Jan|date=2019-03-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-27|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327000633/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/26/health/opioids-purdue-pharma-oklahoma.html|archive-date=2019-03-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-47710332|title=Sackler drug firm settles opioid lawsuit|date=March 26, 2019|work=BBC|access-date=2019-03-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328005752/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-47710332|archive-date=March 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Purdue Pharma and the Sackler family were in negotiations to settle the claims for a payment of $10-$12 billion.\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/purdue-pharma-offers-10-12-billion-settle-opioid-claims-n1046526|title=Purdue Pharma offers $10-12B to settle 2,000+ opioid lawsuits|website=NBC News|access-date=2019-08-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827213906/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/purdue-pharma-offers-10-12-billion-settle-opioid-claims-n1046526|archive-date=2019-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref> The settlement would include a Chapter 11 filing by Purdue Pharma, which would be restructured as [[Trust law|public beneficiary trust]] and the Sackler Family would give up any ownership in the company. Addiction treatment drugs currently developed by the company would be given to the public cost-free. All profits of Purdue would henceforth go to the plaintiffs in the case. On top, the Sackler family would contribute $3 billion in cash. The family would also sell Mundipharma and contribute another $1.5 billion from the sales proceeds to the settlement. However, the Sackler family would remain a billionaire family and would not be criminally charged for contributing to the [[opioid crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/27/health/sacklers-purdue-pharma-opioid-settlement.html|title=Sacklers Would Give Up Ownership of Purdue Pharma Under Settlement Proposal|first=Jan|last=Hoffman|date=August 27, 2019|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=August 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828041034/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/27/health/sacklers-purdue-pharma-opioid-settlement.html|archive-date=August 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 2019, the office of the New York Attorney General accused the Sackler family of hiding money by wiring at least $1 billion from company accounts to personal accounts overseas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/09/13/760688886/new-york-ag-says-sacklers-transferred-millions-from-pharma-accounts-to-themselve|title=New York AG Says Sacklers Transferred $1B From Pharma Accounts To Themselves|website=NPR.org|accessdate=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921113848/https://www.npr.org/2019/09/13/760688886/new-york-ag-says-sacklers-transferred-millions-from-pharma-accounts-to-themselve|archive-date=2019-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/n-y-ag-we-found-1-billion-sackler-wire-transfers-n1054401|title=N.Y. officials: We found $1 billion in Sackler family wire transfers|website=NBC News|accessdate=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920184606/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/n-y-ag-we-found-1-billion-sackler-wire-transfers-n1054401|archive-date=2019-09-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Bankruptcy ==\nIn mid-September 2019, Purdue filed for bankruptcy in White Plains, New York, a few days after reaching a tentative settlement with state and local governments that were suing the company over the cost of the opioid epidemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2019/09/15/purdue-pharma-bankruptcy-oxycontin-maker-filed-chapter-11-sunday/2338793001/|title=OxyContin maker Purdue Pharma files for bankruptcy as part of opioids settlement|last=Mulvihill|first=Geoff|date=15 September 2019|website=USA Today|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916184518/https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2019/09/15/purdue-pharma-bankruptcy-oxycontin-maker-filed-chapter-11-sunday/2338793001/|archive-date=16 September 2019|access-date=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nMany states refused the terms of the proposed August 2019 settlement and vowed to pursue further litigation to recover additional money, much of it alleged to be hidden offshore. These states contend the Sacklers knew litigants would be pursuing Purdue's funds and committed [[fraudulent conveyance]]. Whether or not a state had chosen to settle mostly fell along party lines, with Republican-led states choosing to settle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/n-y-ag-we-found-1-billion-sackler-wire-transfers-n1054401|title=N.Y. officials: We found $1 billion in Sackler family wire transfers|website=NBC News|access-date=2019-09-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914030527/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/n-y-ag-we-found-1-billion-sackler-wire-transfers-n1054401|archive-date=2019-09-14|url-status=live}}</ref> Most of the wealth of the Sackler Family is not held in Purdue. States are seeking to hold individual family members personally liable for the costs of the opioid epidemic, regardless of Purdue's bankruptcy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/new-strategy-suing-opioid-maker-blamed-addiction-crisis-target-family-n883091|title=They're the first family of pharma. And now they're being sued.|website=NBC News|access-date=2019-09-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911231315/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/new-strategy-suing-opioid-maker-blamed-addiction-crisis-target-family-n883091|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hilltopmonitor.com/2019/09/oxycontin-drugmaker-purdue-files-for-bankruptcy/|title=OxyContin drugmaker Purdue files for bankruptcy|website=hilltopmonitor.com}}</ref>\n\nA December 2019 audit from AlixPartners, hired by Purdue for guidance through Chapter 11 restructuring, said the Sacklers withdrew $10.7 billion from Purdue after the company began to receive legal scrutiny.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/16/health/sacklers-purdue-payments-opioids-.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-12-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218142501/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/16/health/sacklers-purdue-payments-opioids-.html |archive-date=2019-12-18 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Richard Sackler]] former chairman and president of Purdue Pharma\n* [[Timeline of the opioid epidemic]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=Pain Killer: An Empire of Deceit and the Origin of America's Opioid Epidemic |year=2018 |author=Barry Meier |publisher=Random House |isbn=978-0525511106}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official}}\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/an-onslaught-of-pills-hundreds-of-thousands-of-deaths-who-is-accountable/2019/07/20/8d85e650-aafc-11e9-86dd-d7f0e60391e9_story.html \"An onslaught of pills, hundreds of thousands of deaths: Who is accountable?\"]\n* [https://www.netflix.com/title/81002576 \"The Pharmacist\"], a Netflix documentary series about the role a Louisiana pharmacist played in exposing corruption behind the opioid addiction crisis.\n\n{{Pharmaceutical companies of the United States}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Pharmaceutical companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Stamford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Drug policy of the United States]]\n[[Category:Sackler family]]\n[[Category:Health care companies based in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Social problems in medicine]]\n[[Category:Corruption in the United States]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1892]]\n[[Category:1892 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Opioid epidemic]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 2019]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American pharmaceutical company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Purdue Pharma L.P.\n| native_name      = Purdue Pharmaceuticals L.P.\n| logo             = Purdue-logo.gif\n| type             = [[private company|Private]]\n| foundation       = [[Manhattan|New York, New York]], USA<br>{{start date and age|1892}}\n| founders         = John Purdue Gray<br>George Frederick Bingham\n| location_city    = [[Stamford, Connecticut]]\n| location_country = U.S.\n| key_people       = Dr. Craig Landau ([[President (corporate title)|President]] & [[CEO]])<br>[[Arthur Sackler]]<br>[[Mortimer Sackler]]<br>[[Raymond Sackler]]\n| industry         = [[pharmaceutical company|Pharmaceuticals]]\n| num_employees    = 5,000 (worldwide)\n| revenue          = {{increase}} $3 billion (2017)\n| homepage         = {{URL|purduepharma.com}} (Global website)\n| footnotes        = {{reflist|group=*}}\n}}\n\n'''Purdue Pharma''' L.P. is a privately held [[pharmaceutical company]] founded by John Purdue Gray. It is owned principally by descendants of [[Mortimer Sackler|Mortimer]] and [[Raymond Sackler]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a12775932/sackler-family-oxycontin/|title=The Secretive Family Making Billions From the Opioid Crisis|last=Glazek|first=Christopher|date=2017-10-16|website=Esquire|access-date=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920060840/https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a12775932/sackler-family-oxycontin/|archive-date=2019-09-20|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain|title=The Family That Built an Empire of Pain|last=Keefe|first=Patrick Radden|date=2017-10-23|work=The New Yorker|accessdate=2018-01-19|issn=0028-792X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122073308/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain|archive-date=2018-01-22|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2007, it paid out one of the largest fines ever levied against a pharmaceutical firm for mislabeling its product [[OxyContin]], and three executives were found guilty of criminal charges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/18591525|title=Purdue Pharma, Execs to Pay $634.5 Million Fine in OxyContin Case|last=AP|date=2007-05-10|website=www.cnbc.com|access-date=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821020738/https://www.cnbc.com/id/18591525|archive-date=2019-08-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Van Zee|first=Art|date=February 2009|title=The Promotion and Marketing of OxyContin: Commercial Triumph, Public Health Tragedy|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=99|issue=2|pages=221\u2013227|doi=10.2105/AJPH.2007.131714|issn=0090-0036|pmc=2622774|pmid=18799767}}</ref> Although the company shifted its focus to abuse-deterrent formulations, Purdue continued to market and sell opioids, and continued to be involved in lawsuits around the [[opioid epidemic in the United States]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/opioid-talks-impasse-purdue-bankruptcy-filing-expected-n1051136|title=Opioid talks break down; Purdue owners balk at paying $4.5 billion|website=NBC News|access-date=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921141532/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/opioid-talks-impasse-purdue-bankruptcy-filing-expected-n1051136|archive-date=2019-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/09/11/759967610/purdue-pharma-reaches-tentative-deal-to-settle-thousands-of-opioid-lawsuits|title=Purdue Pharma Reaches Tentative Deal To Settle Thousands Of Opioid Lawsuits|website=NPR.org|access-date=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921114135/https://www.npr.org/2019/09/11/759967610/purdue-pharma-reaches-tentative-deal-to-settle-thousands-of-opioid-lawsuits|archive-date=2019-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Purdue filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection on September 15, 2019 in New York.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-purdue-pharma-bankruptcy-idUSKBN1W1058|title=OxyContin maker Purdue Pharma files for bankruptcy protection|date=2019-09-17|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921050011/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-purdue-pharma-bankruptcy-idUSKBN1W1058|archive-date=2019-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/15/health/purdue-pharma-bankruptcy-opioids-settlement.html|title=Purdue Pharma, Maker of OxyContin, Files for Bankruptcy|last=Hoffman|first=Jan|date=2019-09-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-09-21|last2=Walsh|first2=Mary Williams|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921101445/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/15/health/purdue-pharma-bankruptcy-opioids-settlement.html|archive-date=2019-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe company that became Purdue Pharma was founded in 1892 by medical doctors John Purdue Gray and George Frederick Bingham in [[Manhattan]] as the Purdue Frederick Company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.purduepharma.com/about/|title=About Purdue Pharma L.P.|author=|date=|website=www.purduepharma.com|accessdate=22 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906101503/http://www.purduepharma.com/about/|archive-date=6 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2018/purdue-university-statement-re-purdue-pharma.html|title=Purdue University statement re: Purdue Pharma|last=Service|first=Purdue News|website=www.purdue.edu|access-date=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921145953/https://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2018/purdue-university-statement-re-purdue-pharma.html|archive-date=2019-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1952, the company was sold to two other medical doctors, brothers [[Raymond Sackler|Raymond]] and [[Mortimer Sackler]], who relocated the business to [[Yonkers, New York]]. At the time, Purdue sold staples like earwax remover and laxatives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain|title=The Family That Built an Empire of Pain|first=Patrick Radden|last=Keefe|date=October 23, 2017|via=www.newyorker.com|access-date=October 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122073308/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain|archive-date=January 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The Sacklers' older brother, [[Arthur Sackler]], held a one-third option in the company, which was sold to his brothers after his death.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hyperallergic.com/422738/elizabeth-sackler-nan-goldin-opioid-epidemic/|title=Elizabeth A. Sackler Supports Nan Goldin in Her Campaign Against OxyContin|date=2018-01-22|work=Hyperallergic|access-date=2018-01-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123035116/https://hyperallergic.com/422738/elizabeth-sackler-nan-goldin-opioid-epidemic/|archive-date=2018-01-23|url-status=live}}</ref> Under the Sacklers, the company opened additional offices in [[New Jersey]] and [[Connecticut]]. The headquarters are in [[Stamford, Connecticut]].\n\nThe present-day company, Purdue Pharma L.P., was incorporated in 1991, and focuses on [[pain management]] medication, calling itself a \"pioneer in developing medications for reducing pain, a principal cause of human suffering\". In September 2015, the company's website said it had some 1,700 people on its payroll.<ref name=\"Purduepharma.com_About\">{{cite web | url=http://www.purduepharma.com/about/ | title=About Purdue Pharma L.P. | accessdate=September 8, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906101503/http://www.purduepharma.com/about/ | archive-date=September 6, 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, the company announced it would acquire VM Pharma, thereby gaining access to worldwide development and commercial rights to an [[allosteric]] selective [[tropomyosin]] receptor [[kinase]] inhibitor program, i.e., the Phase II candidate VM-902A. The deal could generate more than $213 million for VM Pharma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genengnews.com/gen-news-highlights/purdue-pharma-acquires-trka-inhibitor-program-for-up-to-213m/81251701/|title=Purdue Pharma Acquires TrkA Inhibitor Program for Up to $213M+ - GEN|author=|date=|website=GEN|accessdate=22 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023063714/https://www.genengnews.com/gen-news-highlights/purdue-pharma-acquires-trka-inhibitor-program-for-up-to-213m/81251701/|archive-date=23 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe company has never had an affiliation with [[Purdue University]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/purdue-university-statement-says-indiana-school-has-no-ties-to-purdue-pharma/|title=Purdue University must remind people it has no ties to Purdue Pharma|website=www.cbsnews.com|access-date=2019-09-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914202159/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/purdue-university-statement-says-indiana-school-has-no-ties-to-purdue-pharma/|archive-date=2019-09-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nThe company's branches include Purdue Pharma L.P., The Purdue Frederick Company, Purdue Pharmaceutical Products L.P., and Purdue Products L.P.\nThe company's manufacturing takes place at three sites: Purdue Pharmaceuticals L.P., a plant located in [[Wilson, North Carolina]], the P.F. Laboratories, Inc. in [[Totowa, New Jersey]], and Rhodes Technologies L.P., in [[Coventry, Rhode Island]]. Purdue Pharma L.P. also has research labs in [[Cranbury, New Jersey]]. OxyContin is currently distributed throughout the U.S., Canada, and Mexico. Distribution takes place from the P.F. Laboratories in [[Totowa, New Jersey]].\n\n[[Rhodes Pharmaceuticals]] is a sister company that was established in [[Rhode Island]] in 2007. The company is one of the largest producers of off-patent generic opioids in the US.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crow |first1=David |title=Billionaire Sackler family owns second opioid drugmaker |url=https://www.ft.com/content/2d21cf1a-b2bc-11e8-99ca-68cf89602132 |website=Financial Times |accessdate=September 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180915225952/https://www.ft.com/content/2d21cf1a-b2bc-11e8-99ca-68cf89602132 |archive-date=September 15, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSister companies to Purdue that are also controlled by descendants of Mortimer and Raymond Sackler are [[Napp Pharmaceuticals]] in the United Kingdom and Mundipharma<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thefix.com/secretive-billionaire-family-behind-rise-oxycontin |author=Victoria Kim |title=The Secretive Billionaire Family Behind The Rise Of Oxycontin |publisher=The Fix |date=November 3, 2017 |accessdate=February 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223021904/https://www.thefix.com/secretive-billionaire-family-behind-rise-oxycontin |archive-date=February 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> that are selling opioids globally.\n\nNew drugs are being developed under other company names, such as Adlon Therapeutics and Imbrium. Both are based in the same building as their parent company in downtown Stamford, and share employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mysanantonio.com/business/article/FDA-approves-Purdue-Pharma-subsidiary-s-ADHD-13655418.php|title=FDA approves Purdue Pharma subsidiary's ADHD drug|author=Paul Schott|date=March 2019|access-date=2019-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306042804/https://www.mysanantonio.com/business/article/FDA-approves-Purdue-Pharma-subsidiary-s-ADHD-13655418.php|archive-date=2019-03-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Management==\nCraig Landau was appointed CEO on June 22, 2017.<ref name=\"New CEO\">{{cite web |title=Purdue Pharma appoints new CEO |url=https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/business/article/Purdue-Pharma-appoints-new-CEO-11239163.php |date=June 22, 2017 |publisher=[[Stamford Advocate]] |accessdate=May 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521204413/https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/business/article/Purdue-Pharma-appoints-new-CEO-11239163.php |archive-date=May 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He joined Purdue Pharma L.P. in 1999 and was chief medical officer and as vice president of R&D innovation, clinical and medical affairs. In 2013, he was appointed president and CEO of Purdue Pharma (Canada).<ref name=\"Landau\">{{cite web|title=Craig Landau |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=34123931&privcapId=264625 |date= |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy 2018, eight members of the [[Sackler family]] were listed to be active or former members of the Board of Directors.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/46ff5632-b1bd-11e8-99ca-68cf89602132 |author=David Crowe |title=What next for the Sacklers? A pharma dynasty under siege |newspaper=[[Financial Times]] |date=September 8, 2018 |accessdate=February 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327161404/https://www.ft.com/content/46ff5632-b1bd-11e8-99ca-68cf89602132 |archive-date=March 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> By early 2019, the Sacklers had left the Purdue Pharma board, leaving none on the panel. Steve Miller became chairman in July 2018, with a current board left of five members.<ref name=\"Sacklers Quite\">{{cite web |title=Sacklers quit Purdue Pharma board amid shifts for OxyContin maker |url=https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/business/article/Sacklers-quit-Purdue-Pharma-board-signaling-13742946.php |date=April 7, 2019 |work=[[Stamford Advocate]] |publisher=[[Stamford Advocate]] |accessdate=May 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190528151957/https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/business/article/Sacklers-quit-Purdue-Pharma-board-signaling-13742946.php |archive-date=May 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nPurdue Pharma makes pain medicines such as [[hydromorphone]], [[oxycodone]], [[fentanyl]], [[codeine]], and [[hydrocodone]]. It is widely known for the production of drugs such as MS Contin, Oxycontin, and Ryzolt. In 1972, Contin (a controlled drug-release system) was developed. In 1984, its extended-release formulation of morphine, MS Contin was released. In 1996 its extended-release formulation of oxycodone, OxyContin was released.<ref name=\"Purduepharma.com_About\" />\n\nThe controversy behind the company emerged as a result of the drugs that they made and how they carried high potential for addiction. The most commonly abused medications that the company produces are MS Contin and OxyContin. Both can be abused by crushing, chewing, snorting, or injecting the dissolved product. These ingestion methods create a significant risk to the abuser; they can result in overdose and death. Drug-seeking tactics that addicts undergo to obtain the medication include \"[[doctor shopping]]\", which is visiting a number of different physicians to obtain additional prescriptions and refusal to follow up with appropriate examinations. Along with the high potential for abuse among people without prescriptions, there is also a risk for physical dependency and reduced reaction or drug desensitization for patients that are prescribed them. Nevertheless, strong analgesic drugs remain indispensable to patients suffering from severe acute and cancer pain.<ref>World Health Organization. Cancer pain relief and palliative care. Geneva: WHO 1990</ref>\n\nOxyContin, introduced in 1995, was Purdue Pharma's breakthrough palliative for chronic pain. Under a marketing strategy that [[Arthur Sackler]] had pioneered decades earlier, the company aggressively pressed doctors to prescribe the drug, wooing them with free trips to pain-management seminars and paid speaking engagements. Sales soared.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/19/business/raymond-sackler-dead-of-purdue-pharma.html|title=Opinion - Raymond Sackler, Psychopharmacology Pioneer and Philanthropist, Dies at 97|first=Sam|last=Roberts|date=19 July 2017|accessdate=11 February 2018|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228212508/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/19/business/raymond-sackler-dead-of-purdue-pharma.html|archive-date=28 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The drug was marketed as \"smooth and sustained pain control all day and all night\" when taken on a 12-hour schedule and as having lower abuse potential than immediate-release oxycodone because of its time-release properties, even though there was no scientific evidence backing that conclusion and the addictive nature of opiates had been known for thousands of years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-10-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122073308/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain |archive-date=2018-01-22 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://opiateaddictionsupport.com/chasing-heroin-review-frontline-documentary/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307142536/http://opiateaddictionsupport.com/chasing-heroin-review-frontline-documentary/ |archive-date=2016-03-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> In these early years, Purdue Pharma was aware of OxyContin abuse, including \"reports that the pills were being crushed and snorted; stolen from pharmacies; and that some doctors were being charged with selling prescriptions,\" according to ''[[The New York Times]]'', based on a confidential Justice Department report that was revealed in May 2018. Over a hundred internal company memos between 1997 and 1999 included the words \"street value,\" \"crush,\" or \"snort.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Meier|first1=Barry|title=Origins of an Epidemic: Purdue Pharma Knew Its Opioids Were Widely Abused|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/29/health/purdue-opioids-oxycontin.html|accessdate=30 May 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|date=29 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530000118/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/29/health/purdue-opioids-oxycontin.html|archive-date=30 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the start of 2000, widespread reports of OxyContin abuse surfaced. The results obtained from a proactive abuse surveillance program called Researched Abused, Diversion, and Addiction-Related Surveillance (RADARS) sponsored by Purdue Pharma L.P. pronounced Oxycontin and hydrocodone the most commonly abused pain medications.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Cicero TJ, Inciardi JA, Mu\u00f1oz A |title=Trends in abuse of Oxycontin and other opioid analgesics in the United States: 2002-2004 |journal=Journal of Pain |volume=6 |issue=10 |pages=662\u201372 |year=2005 |pmid=16202959 |doi=10.1016/j.jpain.2005.05.004 |url=}}</ref> In 2012, New England Journal of Medicine published a study that found that \"76 percent of those seeking help for heroin addiction began by abusing pharmaceutical narcotics, primarily OxyContin\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Jason|title=Kingpins: OxyContin, Heroin, and the Sackler-Sinaloa Connection|url=https://addictionunscripted.com/kingpinsoxycontin-heroin-and-the-sackler-sinaloa-connection/|accessdate=4 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307210054/https://addictionunscripted.com/kingpinsoxycontin-heroin-and-the-sackler-sinaloa-connection/|archive-date=7 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and drew a direct line between Purdue's marketing of OxyContin and the subsequent heroin epidemic in the U.S.\n\nIn 2003, the Drug Enforcement Administration found that Purdue's \"aggressive methods\" had \"very much exacerbated OxyContin's widespread abuse.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain|title=The Family That Built an Empire of Pain|first=Patrick Radden|last=Keefe|date=23 October 2017|accessdate=27 March 2019|via=www.newyorker.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122073308/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain|archive-date=22 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA 2016, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' investigation reported that in many people OxyContin's 12-hour schedule does not adequately control pain, resulting in withdrawal symptoms including intense craving for the drug. The journalists suggested that this problem gives \"new insight into why so many people have become addicted.\" Using Purdue documents and other records, they claim that Purdue was aware of this problem even before the drug went to market but \"held fast to the claim of 12-hour relief, in part to protect its revenue [because] OxyContin's market dominance and its high price \u2014 up to hundreds of dollars per bottle \u2014 hinge on its 12-hour duration.\"<ref name=\"latimes_Hell_oxycontin_2016\">{{cite web |title='You want a description of hell?' OxyContin's 12-hour problem |url=http://www.latimes.com/projects/oxycontin-part1/ |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=October 18, 2017 |last1=Harriet |first1=Ryan |first2=Lisa |last2=Girion |first3=Scott |last3=Glover |date=May 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124015217/http://www.latimes.com/projects/oxycontin-part1/ |archive-date=January 24, 2018 |url-status=live }} This is an in-depth series.</ref>\n\nOxyContin became a blockbuster drug. \"Between 1995 and 2001, OxyContin brought in $2.8 billion in revenue for Purdue Pharma.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/10/business/11drug-web.html |title=In Guilty Plea, OxyContin Maker to Pay $600 Million |first=Barry |last=Meier |date=May 10, 2007 |access-date=October 26, 2017 |newspaper=The New York Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027035616/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/10/business/11drug-web.html |archive-date=October 27, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cumulative revenues had increased to US$31 billion by 2016<ref name=\"latimes_Hell_oxycontin_2016\"/> and US$35 billion by 2017.<ref name=\"newyorker_2017_Sackler\"/> According to a 2017 article in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Purdue Pharma is \"owned by one of America's richest families, with a collective net worth of thirteen billion dollars\".<ref name=\"newyorker_2017_Sackler\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain |series=A Reporter at Large |date=October 2017 |title=The Family That Built an Empire of Pain: The Sackler dynasty's ruthless marketing of painkillers has generated billions of dollars\u2014and millions of addicts |first=Patrick Radden |last=Keefe |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=October 26, 2017 |quote=\"According to Forbes, the Sacklers are now one of America's richest families, with a collective net worth of thirteen billion dollars\u2014more than the Rockefellers or the Mellons... While the Sacklers are interviewed regularly on the subject of their generosity, they almost never speak publicly about the family business, Purdue Pharma\u2014a privately held company, based in Stamford, Connecticut, that developed the prescription painkiller OxyContin.\" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122073308/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/10/30/the-family-that-built-an-empire-of-pain |archive-date=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live }} Indepth-analysis</ref> Many US states allege the family is worth more than $13 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49702413|title=Sackler family 'funnelled cash into Swiss banks'|date=September 14, 2019|via=www.bbc.com|access-date=September 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916180158/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49702413|archive-date=September 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In response to this and other journalism, photographer [[Nan Goldin]] launched the organization [[P.A.I.N.]], to pressure museums and other cultural institutions to divest from Sackler Family philanthropy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-06/sackler-family-faces-art-world-protests-with-purdue-under-siege|title=Artists Protest Sackler Family Through Museums That Bear Their Name|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bloomberg.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416181229/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-06/sackler-family-faces-art-world-protests-with-purdue-under-siege|archive-date=2019-04-16|url-status=live|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Purdue Pharma patented a new form of buprenorphine, which controls cravings and is used to treat addiction to opioids such as OxyContin.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ivanova |first1=Irina |title=OxyContin maker gets patent for drug to treat opioid addiction |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/oxycontin-maker-receives-patent-for-drug-to-treat-opioid-addiction |accessdate=9 September 2018 |agency=CBS News |date=7 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908123341/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/oxycontin-maker-receives-patent-for-drug-to-treat-opioid-addiction/ |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Oxycontin-related lawsuits==\nPurdue has been involved in measures against prescription drug abuse, particularly of [[OxyContin|Oxycontin]], an addiction-causing prescription drug which is among the drugs most commonly cited in connection with overdose deaths. In 2001, [[Connecticut Attorney General]] [[Richard Blumenthal]] issued a statement urging Purdue to take action regarding abuse of Oxycontin; he did note that while Purdue seemed sincere, there was little action being taken beyond \"cosmetic and symbolic steps.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/AG/cwp/view.asp?A=1776&Q=283348|title=CT Attorney General|first=Office of the Attorney|last=General|date=|website=www.ct.gov|accessdate=22 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061219073015/http://www.ct.gov/ag/cwp/view.asp?A=1776&Q=283348|archive-date=19 December 2006|url-status=live}}</ref> After Purdue announced plans to [[Pharmaceutical formulation|reformulate the drug]], Blumenthal noted that this would take time and that \"Purdue Pharma has a moral, if not legal obligation to take effective steps and address addiction and abuse even as it works to reformulate the drug.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/AG/cwp/view.asp?A=1776&Q=283344|title=CT Attorney General|first=Office of the Attorney|last=General|date=|website=www.ct.gov|accessdate=22 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061219073036/http://www.ct.gov/ag/cwp/view.asp?A=1776&Q=283344|archive-date=19 December 2006|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the [[West Virginia Attorney General]] sued Purdue for reimbursement of \"excessive prescription costs\" paid by the state. Saying that patients were taking more of the drug than they had been prescribed because the effects of the drug wore off hours before the 12-hour schedule, the state charged Purdue with [[deceptive marketing]]. In his ruling the trial judge wrote: \"Plaintiff's evidence shows Purdue could have tested the safety and efficacy of OxyContin at eight hours, and could have amended their label, but did not.\" The case never went to trial; Purdue agreed to settle by paying the state {{US$|10 million}} (equivalent to approximately ${{inflation|US|10|2004}}M in {{inflation/year|US}}) for programs to discourage drug abuse, with all the evidence remaining under seal and confidential.<ref name=\"latimes_Hell_oxycontin_2016\"/>\n\nIn May 2007, the company [[pleaded guilty]] to misleading the public about Oxycontin's risk of addiction and agreed to pay {{US$|600 million|long=no}} (equivalent to approximately ${{inflation|US|600|2007}}M in {{inflation/year|US}}) in one of the [[List of Largest Pharmaceutical Settlements|largest pharmaceutical settlements in U.S. history]]. The company's [[President (corporate title)|president]] (Michael Friedman), top lawyer (Howard R. Udell) and former [[Chief Medical Officer|chief medical officer]] (Paul D. Goldenheim) pleaded guilty as individuals to [[Pharmaceutical fraud#Off-label marketing|misbranding]] charges, a criminal violation and agreed to pay a total of {{US$|34.5 million}} in fines.<ref>Sue Lindsey, (May 11, 2007) [https://www.usatoday.com/money/economy/2007-05-10-1771944037_x.htm OxyContin Maker, Execs Guilty of Deceit] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120911005434/http://www.usatoday.com/money/economy/2007-05-10-1771944037_x.htm |date=2012-09-11 }} [[USA Today]] reproducing and [[Associated Press]] report</ref><ref>Barry Meier, (May 11, 2007) \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/11/business/11drug-web.html?_r=1&hp In Guilty Plea, OxyContin Maker to Pay $600 Million\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611003513/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/11/business/11drug-web.html?_r=1&hp |date=2015-06-11 }}, New York Times</ref> Friedman, Udell and Goldenheim agreed to pay {{US$|19 million}}, {{US$|8 million}} and {{US$|7.5 million}}, respectively. In addition three top executives were charged with a felony and sentenced to 400 hours of [[Community service#Court ordered service|community service]] in drug treatment programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.domain-b.com/industry/pharma/2007/20070722_purdue_pharma.html|title=domain-b.com : Purdue Pharma fined $634 million for OxyContin deaths; executives punished|author=|date=July 22, 2007|website=www.domain-b.com|accessdate=22 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206000554/http://domain-b.com/industry/pharma/2007/20070722_purdue_pharma.html|archive-date=6 February 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn October 4, 2007, Kentucky officials sued Purdue because of widespread Oxycontin abuse in Appalachia. A lawsuit filed by Kentucky then-Attorney General Greg Stumbo and Pike County officials demanded millions in compensation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/economy/2007-10-04-3869518294_x.htm|title=Kentucky sues makers of OxyContin - USATODAY.com|author=|date=|website=usatoday30.usatoday.com|accessdate=22 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814191254/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/economy/2007-10-04-3869518294_x.htm|archive-date=14 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Eight years later, on December 23, 2015, Kentucky settled with Purdue for $24 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/kentucky-settles-lawsuit-with-oxycontin-maker-for-24-million/|title=Kentucky settles lawsuit with OxyContin maker for $24 million|website=www.cbsnews.com|access-date=2016-05-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430040604/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/kentucky-settles-lawsuit-with-oxycontin-maker-for-24-million/|archive-date=2016-04-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, the city of [[Everett, Washington]] sued Purdue based on increased costs for the city from the use of oxycontin as well as Purdue not intervening when they noted odd patterns of sale of their product, per agreement in the 2007 suit noted above. The allegations include not following legal agreements to track suspicious excess ordering or potential black market usage. False clinics created by unscrupulous doctors using homeless individuals as 'patients' to purchase oxycontin, then sell to the citizens of Everett was the factual basis of the suit.<ref name=\"Harriet Ryan\">{{citation|title=City devastated by OxyContin use sues Purdue Pharma, claims drugmaker put profits over citizens' welfare|author=Harriet Ryan|date=January 19, 2017|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-oxycontin-lawsuit-20170118-story.html|access-date=May 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601133439/http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-oxycontin-lawsuit-20170118-story.html|archive-date=June 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Scott North\">{{citation|newspaper=Everett Herald|title=Everett's suit against OxyContin maker moves to federal court|author=Scott North|date=February 20, 2017|url=http://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-suit-against-oxycontin-maker-moves-to-federal-court/|access-date=May 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228194350/http://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-suit-against-oxycontin-maker-moves-to-federal-court/|archive-date=February 28, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Morning Edition\">{{citation|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/02/03/513196772/u-s-city-sues-oxycontin-maker-for-contributing-to-opiod-crisis|title=U.S. City Sues OxyContin Maker For Contributing To Opioid Crisis|work=[[Morning Edition]]|publisher=NPR|date=February 3, 2017|access-date=April 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313190130/https://www.npr.org/2017/02/03/513196772/u-s-city-sues-oxycontin-maker-for-contributing-to-opiod-crisis|archive-date=March 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe blackmarket sale of the drug out of legal pharmacies based in Los Angeles with distributions points in Everett is also part of the experience of the city. No intervention was made by Purdue to contact the DEA for years despite knowing of the practice and the overuse and sale of their product. The suit is asking for a yet to be determined reimbursement related to costs of policing, housing, health care, rehabilitation, criminal justice system, park and recreations department, as well as to the loss of life or compromised quality of life of the citizens of Everett directly.<ref name=\"Harriet Ryan\"/><ref name=\"Scott North\"/><ref name=\"Morning Edition\"/>\n\nIn May 2018, six states \u2014 Florida, Nevada, North Carolina, North Dakota, Tennessee and Texas \u2014 filed lawsuits charging deceptive marketing practices, adding to 16 previously filed lawsuits by other U.S. states and Puerto Rico.<ref name=\"Reuters May 10, 2018\">{{cite web |last1=Bellon |first1=Tina |title=U.S. state lawsuits against Purdue Pharma over opioid epidemic mount |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-opioids-litigation/u-s-state-attorneys-general-sue-purdue-pharma-over-opioid-epidemic-idUSKCN1IG2WU |website=Reuters |accessdate=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614152013/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-opioids-litigation/u-s-state-attorneys-general-sue-purdue-pharma-over-opioid-epidemic-idUSKCN1IG2WU |archive-date=14 June 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"USA Today May 2018\">{{cite web |last1=Moritz |first1=John C. |title=6 states sue maker of OxyContin as they battle expenses, human costs of opioid crisis |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2018/05/15/six-attorney-generals-opioid-lawsuits/612721002/ |website=USA TODAY |publisher=Corpus Christi (Texas) Caller Times |accessdate=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528110904/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2018/05/15/six-attorney-generals-opioid-lawsuits/612721002/ |archive-date=28 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> By January 2019, 36 states were suing Purdue Pharma. Massachusetts attorney general Maura Healey complains in her lawsuit that eight members of the Sackler family are \"personally responsible\" for the deception. She alleges they \"micromanaged\" a \"deceptive sales campaign.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/purdue-pharma-lawsuit-massachusetts-attorney-general-blames-sackler-family-for-creating-opioid-crisis-oxycontin/|title=Family behind OxyContin maker engineered opioid crisis, Massachusetts AG says|last=|first=|date=24 January 2019|website=CBS News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190127234253/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/purdue-pharma-lawsuit-massachusetts-attorney-general-blames-sackler-family-for-creating-opioid-crisis-oxycontin/|archive-date=27 January 2019|url-status=live|access-date=2019-01-28}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Purdue Pharma reached a $270m settlement in a lawsuit,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/5732644-Oklahoma-sopioidlawsuitpetition.html|title=Oklahoma'sopioidlawsuitpetition|last=Frontier)|first=Kassie McClung (The|website=www.documentcloud.org|access-date=2019-03-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327071316/https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/5732644-Oklahoma-sopioidlawsuitpetition.html|archive-date=2019-03-27|url-status=live}}</ref> filed by Oklahoma, which claimed its opioids contributed to the deaths of thousands of people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/26/health/opioids-purdue-pharma-oklahoma.html|title=Purdue Pharma and Sacklers Reach $270 Million Settlement in Opioid Lawsuit|last=Hoffman|first=Jan|date=2019-03-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-27|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327000633/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/26/health/opioids-purdue-pharma-oklahoma.html|archive-date=2019-03-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-47710332|title=Sackler drug firm settles opioid lawsuit|date=March 26, 2019|work=BBC|access-date=2019-03-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328005752/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-47710332|archive-date=March 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Purdue Pharma and the Sackler family were in negotiations to settle the claims for a payment of $10-$12 billion.\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/purdue-pharma-offers-10-12-billion-settle-opioid-claims-n1046526|title=Purdue Pharma offers $10-12B to settle 2,000+ opioid lawsuits|website=NBC News|access-date=2019-08-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827213906/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/purdue-pharma-offers-10-12-billion-settle-opioid-claims-n1046526|archive-date=2019-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref> The settlement would include a Chapter 11 filing by Purdue Pharma, which would be restructured as [[Trust law|public beneficiary trust]] and the Sackler Family would give up any ownership in the company. Addiction treatment drugs currently developed by the company would be given to the public cost-free. All profits of Purdue would henceforth go to the plaintiffs in the case. On top, the Sackler family would contribute $3 billion in cash. The family would also sell Mundipharma and contribute another $1.5 billion from the sales proceeds to the settlement. However, the Sackler family would remain a billionaire family and would not be criminally charged for contributing to the [[opioid crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/27/health/sacklers-purdue-pharma-opioid-settlement.html|title=Sacklers Would Give Up Ownership of Purdue Pharma Under Settlement Proposal|first=Jan|last=Hoffman|date=August 27, 2019|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=August 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828041034/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/27/health/sacklers-purdue-pharma-opioid-settlement.html|archive-date=August 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 2019, the office of the New York Attorney General accused the Sackler family of hiding money by wiring at least $1 billion from company accounts to personal accounts overseas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/09/13/760688886/new-york-ag-says-sacklers-transferred-millions-from-pharma-accounts-to-themselve|title=New York AG Says Sacklers Transferred $1B From Pharma Accounts To Themselves|website=NPR.org|accessdate=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921113848/https://www.npr.org/2019/09/13/760688886/new-york-ag-says-sacklers-transferred-millions-from-pharma-accounts-to-themselve|archive-date=2019-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/n-y-ag-we-found-1-billion-sackler-wire-transfers-n1054401|title=N.Y. officials: We found $1 billion in Sackler family wire transfers|website=NBC News|accessdate=2019-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920184606/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/n-y-ag-we-found-1-billion-sackler-wire-transfers-n1054401|archive-date=2019-09-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Bankruptcy ==\nIn mid-September 2019, Purdue filed for bankruptcy in White Plains, New York, a few days after reaching a tentative settlement with state and local governments that were suing the company over the cost of the opioid epidemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2019/09/15/purdue-pharma-bankruptcy-oxycontin-maker-filed-chapter-11-sunday/2338793001/|title=OxyContin maker Purdue Pharma files for bankruptcy as part of opioids settlement|last=Mulvihill|first=Geoff|date=15 September 2019|website=USA Today|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916184518/https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2019/09/15/purdue-pharma-bankruptcy-oxycontin-maker-filed-chapter-11-sunday/2338793001/|archive-date=16 September 2019|access-date=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nMany states refused the terms of the proposed August 2019 settlement and vowed to pursue further litigation to recover additional money, much of it alleged to be hidden offshore. These states contend the Sacklers knew litigants would be pursuing Purdue's funds and committed [[fraudulent conveyance]]. Whether or not a state had chosen to settle mostly fell along party lines, with Republican-led states choosing to settle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/n-y-ag-we-found-1-billion-sackler-wire-transfers-n1054401|title=N.Y. officials: We found $1 billion in Sackler family wire transfers|website=NBC News|access-date=2019-09-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914030527/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/n-y-ag-we-found-1-billion-sackler-wire-transfers-n1054401|archive-date=2019-09-14|url-status=live}}</ref> Most of the wealth of the Sackler Family is not held in Purdue. States are seeking to hold individual family members personally liable for the costs of the opioid epidemic, regardless of Purdue's bankruptcy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/new-strategy-suing-opioid-maker-blamed-addiction-crisis-target-family-n883091|title=They're the first family of pharma. And now they're being sued.|website=NBC News|access-date=2019-09-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911231315/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/new-strategy-suing-opioid-maker-blamed-addiction-crisis-target-family-n883091|archive-date=2019-09-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hilltopmonitor.com/2019/09/oxycontin-drugmaker-purdue-files-for-bankruptcy/|title=OxyContin drugmaker Purdue files for bankruptcy|website=hilltopmonitor.com}}</ref>\n\nA December 2019 audit from AlixPartners, hired by Purdue for guidance through Chapter 11 restructuring, said the Sacklers withdrew $10.7 billion from Purdue after the company began to receive legal scrutiny.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/16/health/sacklers-purdue-payments-opioids-.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-12-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218142501/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/16/health/sacklers-purdue-payments-opioids-.html |archive-date=2019-12-18 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Richard Sackler]] former chairman and president of Purdue Pharma\n* [[Timeline of the opioid epidemic]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=Pain Killer: An Empire of Deceit and the Origin of America's Opioid Epidemic |year=2018 |author=Barry Meier |publisher=Random House |isbn=978-0525511106}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official}}\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/an-onslaught-of-pills-hundreds-of-thousands-of-deaths-who-is-accountable/2019/07/20/8d85e650-aafc-11e9-86dd-d7f0e60391e9_story.html \"An onslaught of pills, hundreds of thousands of deaths: Who is accountable?\"]\n* [https://www.netflix.com/title/81002576 \"The Pharmacist\"], a Netflix documentary series about the role a Louisiana pharmacist played in exposing corruption behind the opioid addiction crisis.\n\n{{Pharmaceutical companies of the United States}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Pharmaceutical companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Stamford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Drug policy of the United States]]\n[[Category:Sackler family]]\n[[Category:Health care companies based in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Social problems in medicine]]\n[[Category:Corruption in the United States]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1892]]\n[[Category:1892 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Opioid epidemic]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 2019]]\n", "name_user": "Under Mifflin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Purdue_Pharma"}
{"title_page": "1980 Texas Rangers season", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox MLB yearly\n| name = Texas Rangers\n| season = 1980\n| misc =\n| logo = TexasRangers 100.png\n| current league = American League\n| y1 = 1961\n| division = [[American League West|Western Division]]\n| y2 = 1972\n| Uniform logo =\n| ballpark = [[Arlington Stadium]]\n| y4 = 1972\n| city = [[Arlington, Texas]]\n| y5 = 1972\n| owners = [[Eddie Chiles]]\n| general managers = [[Eddie Robinson (baseball)|Eddie Robinson]]\n| managers = [[Pat Corrales]]\n| television = [[KXAS-TV]]<br>([[Frank Glieber]], [[Eric Nadel]], [[Mel Proctor]])\n| radio = [[WBAP (AM)|WBAP]]<br>([[Eric Nadel]], Bill Merrill, [[Mel Proctor]])\n|}}\n\nThe '''[[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] [[1980 in baseball|1980 season]]''' involved the Rangers finishing 4th in the [[American League]] west with a record of 76 wins and 85 losses.\n\n== Offseason ==\n* November 14, 1979: [[Eric Soderholm]] was traded by the Texas Rangers to the New York Yankees for players to be named later and cash. The New York Yankees sent Amos Lewis (minors) (December 13, 1979) and Ricky Burdette (minors) (December 13, 1979) to the Texas Rangers to complete the trade.<ref>https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/s/soderer01.shtml</ref>\n* December 6, 1979: [[Doyle Alexander]], [[Larvell Blanks]] and $50,000 were traded by the Rangers to the [[Atlanta Braves]] for [[Adrian Devine]] and [[Pepe Fr\u00edas]].<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/a/alexado01.shtml Doyle Alexander page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n* January 4, 1980: [[Larry McCall]], [[Gary Gray (baseball)|Gary Gray]], and Mike Bucci (minors) were traded by the Rangers to the [[Cleveland Indians]] for [[David Clyde]] and [[Jim Norris]].<ref name=clyde>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/c/clydeda01.shtml David Clyde page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n* January 11, 1980: [[1980 Major League Baseball Draft]]\n**[[Billy Taylor (1990s pitcher)|Billy Taylor]] was drafted by the Rangers in the 2nd round. Player signed March 24, 1980.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/t/taylobi04.shtml Billy Taylor page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n**[[Al Newman]] was drafted by the Rangers in the 3rd round, but did not sign.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/n/newmaal01.shtml Al Newman page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n**[[Daryl Smith (baseball)|Daryl Smith]] was drafted by the Rangers in the 6th round.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/s/smithda04.shtml Daryl Smith page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n* February 15, 1980: [[Willie Monta\u00f1ez]] was traded by the Rangers to the [[San Diego Padres]] for [[Gaylord Perry]], [[Tucker Ashford]] and Joe Carroll (minors).<ref name=perry>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/p/perryga01.shtml Gaylord Perry page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n* March 31, 1980: [[La Rue Washington]] and [[Chris Smith (first baseman)|Chris Smith]] were traded by the Rangers to the [[Montreal Expos]] for [[Rusty Staub]].<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/s/staubru01.shtml Rusty Staub page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n* March 31, 1980: David Clyde was released by the Rangers.<ref name=clyde/>\n\n== Regular season ==\n\n=== Season standings ===\n{{1980 AL West Standings}}\n\n=== Record vs. opponents ===\n{{1980 AL Record vs. opponents|team=TEX}}\n\n=== Notable transactions ===\n* June 3, 1980: [[Tom Henke]] was drafted by the Rangers in the 4th round of the [[1980 Major League Baseball Draft]] (Secondary Phase).<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/h/henketo01.shtml Tom Henke page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n* July 11, 1980: [[Charlie Hough]] was purchased by the Rangers from the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]].<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/h/houghch01.shtml Charlie Hough page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n* August 14, 1980: [[Gaylord Perry]] was traded by the Rangers to the [[New York Yankees]] for [[Ken Clay]] and a player to be named later. The Yankees completed the deal by sending Marvin Thompson (minors) to the Rangers on October 1.<ref name=perry />\n* September 13, 1980: [[Sparky Lyle]] was traded by the Rangers to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] for a player to be named later. The Phillies completed the deal by sending [[Kevin Saucier]] to the Rangers on November 19.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/l/lylesp01.shtml Sparky Lyle page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n\n=== Roster ===\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\" style=\"background-color: red; color: #FFFDD0; text-align: center;\" | 1980 Texas Rangers roster\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" style=\"background-color: #003366; color: #FFFDD0; text-align: center;\" | '''Roster'''\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Pitchers'''\n{{MLBplayer|23|[[Brian Allard]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|46|[[Bob Babcock (baseball)|Bob Babcock]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|29|[[John Butcher (baseball)|John Butcher]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|16|[[Ken Clay]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|11|[[Steve Comer]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|44|[[Danny Darwin]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|35|[[Adrian Devine]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|24|[[Ed Figueroa]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|27|[[Jerry Don Gleaton]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|49|[[Charlie Hough]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|31|[[Ferguson Jenkins]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|38|[[John Henry Johnson (baseball)|John Henry Johnson]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|43|[[Don Kainer]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|34|[[Jim Kern]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|28|[[Dennis Lewallyn]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|28|[[Sparky Lyle]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|32|[[Jon Matlack]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|33|[[Doc Medich]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|36|[[Gaylord Perry]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|26|[[Dave Rajsich]]}}\n| width=\"25px\" | \n| valign=\"top\" | '''Catchers'''\n{{MLBplayer|10|[[Jim Sundberg]]}}\n'''Infielders'''\n{{MLBplayer|29|[[Tucker Ashford]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|25|[[Buddy Bell]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|12|[[Odie Davis]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;9|[[John Ellis (baseball)|John Ellis]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;3|[[Pepe Fr\u00edas]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;7|[[Bud Harrelson]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;4|[[Nelson Norman]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|18|[[Pat Putnam]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;2|[[Mike Richardt]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|1